Recall that in complex analysis, if a function is complex-differentiable (holomorphic) on a domain, then it is also smooth (infinitely differentiable as a real function) on that domain. This is because the complex derivative imposes much stronger conditions than the real derivative, and holomorphic functions are analytic.

Thus, the proof can directly use the fact that `Φ₃' r` is holomorphic to deduce that it is `C^∞` as a real function on `upperHalfPlaneSet`.

